              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>Note that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\widetilde {X}]]></fr:tex> is homotopically equivalent to each of the fibres <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_t=f^{-1}(t)]]></fr:tex> (for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t\in  D^*]]></fr:tex>): <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^i(X_{\overline {K}},\mathbb {Z}_l)]]></fr:tex> is again analogous to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^i(X_t,\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex>, and the transformation of the monodromy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> corresponds to the action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Here, again, we know that a subgroup of finite index of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(D^*)]]></fr:tex> acts unipotently on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^i(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})=H^i(X_t,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.
  We place ourselves in the semi-stable case, where all of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(D^*)]]></fr:tex> acts unipotently (this reduces to replacing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> by a finite covering), and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> be the action of the canonical generator of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(D^*)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>By <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-i-3" href="hodge-theory-i-3.xml" number="3" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-i-8" href="hodge-theory-i-8.xml" number="8" />, we expect for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^i(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})\simeq  H^i(X_t,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> to be endowed with an increasing filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex>, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_n^W(H^i(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q}))]]></fr:tex> to be endowed with a Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\log  T(W_n)\subset  W_{n-2}]]></fr:tex>, and for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\log  T]]></fr:tex> to induce a morphism of Hodge structures
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[     M_n\colon  \mathbb {Z}(-1)\otimes \operatorname {Gr}_n^W(H^i)     \to  \operatorname {Gr}_{n-2}^W(H^i).   ]]></fr:tex>
  We would further like for <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-i-8.2" href="hodge-theory-i-8.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="8.2" />, and not just <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-i-8.3" href="hodge-theory-i-8.3.xml" taxon="Equation" number="8.3" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-i-8.4" href="hodge-theory-i-8.4.xml" taxon="Equation" number="8.4" />, to have an analogue.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>We have in fact managed to define, for each vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> of the tangent space to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{0\}]]></fr:tex>, a mixed Hodge structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {H}_u]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^i(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex>.
  The filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> and the Hodge structures on the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_n^W(H^i)]]></fr:tex> are independent of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex>, and the dependence on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {H}_u]]></fr:tex> can be expressed simply in terms of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex>.
  
  Analogously to <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-i-8.2" href="hodge-theory-i-8.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="8.2" />, we find that, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\log  T]]></fr:tex> induces a homomorphism of mixed Hodge structures
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[     M\colon  \mathbb {Z}(1)\otimes  H^i(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Z})     \to  H^i(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Z}).   ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>Finally, the analogy in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-i-8.5" href="hodge-theory-i-8.5.xml" number="8.5" /> is not misleading (but here, the fact that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f|D^*]]></fr:tex> is assumed to be proper and smooth is probably essential).
  We can prove that
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[     (\log  T)^k\colon  \operatorname {Gr}_{n+k}^W(H^n(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q}))     \to  \operatorname {Gr}_{n-k}^W(H^n(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q}))   ]]></fr:tex>
  is an isomorphism for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> (cf. [<fr:link type="local" href="W1958.xml" addr="W1958" title="Introduction à L'Étude des Variétés Kählériennes">W1958</fr:link>, IV 6, Corollary to Theorem 5]).
  This characterises the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex>.
  Until now, we have only had an analogue of the positivity theorem of Hodge (cf. [<fr:link type="local" href="W1958.xml" addr="W1958" title="Introduction à L'Étude des Variétés Kählériennes">W1958</fr:link>, IV 7, Corollary to Theorem 7]) in very particular cases.
  We hope that the mixed structures <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {H}_u]]></fr:tex> determine the asymptotic behaviour, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t\to 0]]></fr:tex>, of the family of pure structures <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H^i(X,\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex> (for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t\in  D^*]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
